---
import BlogLayout from "../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro";

const bodyContent = `
  <h2>Services Are Agents Too</h2>
  <p>The standard mental model for AI agents is a process that takes requests and produces results. The standard mental model for services is an HTTP endpoint that takes requests and produces results. These are the same thing — and the line between them is dissolving.</p>
  <p>Service agents are processes that expose capabilities over a peer-to-peer overlay network instead of the public internet. No load balancer. No exposed port. No API key rotation. Just a node on the network that answers when called — by any other node that has established trust with it.</p>

  <h2>The Pattern</h2>
  <p>A service agent does three things:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>It listens to its inbox for incoming command messages.</li>
    <li>It translates each command into a call against a local HTTP service.</li>
    <li>It sends the response back to the originating node over the same encrypted channel.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>The calling agent never opens a socket to the service directly. It sends a structured message — a command name and a body — through the overlay. The service agent receives it, does the work, and replies. The caller's inbox gets the response. The whole exchange is encrypted, authenticated, and traverses NAT without configuration.</p>

  <pre><code>pilotctl scriptorium stockmarket "from: 2026-04-07"
# → overlay → remote inbox → responder → localhost:8100 → reply → local inbox</code></pre>

  <h2>What This Changes</h2>
  <p>The traditional approach to exposing a service is to put it on the internet: assign an IP, open a port, issue credentials, manage TLS. Every caller needs to know the address. Every address needs to be secured.</p>
  <p>Service agents invert this. The service runs wherever it makes sense — close to the data, close to the GPU, inside a VPC. It registers a node identity on the overlay. Callers find it by name and trust it explicitly. There is no public endpoint to attack and no credential to rotate.</p>
  <p>A Gemini model running on a GCP VM, a database query executor in a private subnet, a market data feed on a dedicated machine — all of these become callable from any node on the network with a single trust relationship and a message.</p>

  <h2>The Responder</h2>
  <p>The service agent runtime — the <em>responder</em> — is a small binary that bridges the overlay network and local HTTP services. It polls the pilot inbox, parses incoming messages as <code>{"command": "...", "body": "..."}</code>, validates the command against a local config file, extracts named parameters via regex, builds an HTTP request, and sends the result back to the caller.</p>

  <pre><code>commands:
  - name: stockmarket
    link: http://localhost:8100/summaries/stockmarket
    arg_regex: '^from:\\s*(?P&lt;from&gt;\\d{4}-\\d{2}-\\d{2})...$'
  - name: polymarket
    link: http://localhost:8100/summaries/polymarket
    arg_regex: '^from:\\s*(?P&lt;from&gt;\\d{4}-\\d{2}-\\d{2}T...)...$'</code></pre>

  <p>Named capture groups in the regex become query parameters. Any HTTP service becomes a callable service agent in about ten lines of YAML.</p>

  <h2>Trust Without Configuration</h2>
  <p>Service agents can run with <code>--trust-auto-approve</code> — a daemon flag that accepts handshake requests from any node automatically. This is appropriate for services designed to be broadly accessible on the network: any node that knows the service exists and sends a handshake can call it immediately, without manual approval on the service side.</p>
  <p>For tighter access control, handshakes can be approved selectively or scoped to a private network. The service agent does not change — only the trust policy does.</p>

  <h2>Where This Goes</h2>
  <p>The overlay network creates a substrate where any process can be a service and any agent can be a caller. The Scriptorium market intelligence feeds, a local LLM, a vector database, a code execution sandbox — these do not need to be cloud APIs. They can be nodes on a private network, callable by identity, with no public surface at all.</p>
  <p>The agent internet is not a new cloud. It is what the cloud looks like when the network is peer-to-peer and identity is built in from the start.</p>
`;
